entries.title: Fugitive $100 million New Jersey deli defendant Peter Coker Jr. arrested in Thailand
entries.description: Hometown International, which only owned a small New Jersey deli, was once valued at $100 million on the stock market.

entries.title: Apple is the only tech giant that still hasn't announced layoffs — these charts may explain why
entries.description: The tech giants went on a hiring spree over the last few years, with one exception.

entries.title: Crypto publication CoinDesk hires Lazard to explore sale as crisis deepens at parent company DCG
entries.description: Crypto publication CoinDesk has engaged Lazard to mull a full or partial sale of the business, a subsidiary of Barry Silbert's Digital Currency Group.

entries.title: Mexico cracks down on solar geoengineering, forcing startup to pause operations
entries.description: Make Sunsets was testing the idea of cooling the atmosphere with sunlight-reflecting chemicals in Baja, but came under widespread criticism.

entries.title: Marvel movies are set to return to China, but Covid could weigh on ticket sales
entries.description: Marvel movies "Black Panther: Wakanda Forever" and "Ant-Man and the Wasp: Quantumania" will open in China in February.

entries.title: A debt ceiling standoff may trigger 'serious' fallout for Americans, warns economist. Here's what it means for you
entries.description: The U.S. will likely hit its $31.4 trillion debt ceiling Thursday. A default could follow, would have far-reaching negative impacts for consumers and investors.

entries.title: Disney slams Peltz for lack of media experience, but its board is light on it, too
entries.description: Disney's board is almost entirely made up of executives who lack media and entertainment experience.

entries.title: Columbia University will be led by a woman for the first time in its 268-year history
entries.description: Columbia University's board of trustees announces Nemat Shafik will be their first woman president after 268 years.

entries.title: Davos elites see a major risk ahead for markets with looming U.S. debt standoff
entries.description: Budding optimism at the annual meeting of billionaires, heads of state and business leaders in the Swiss Alps collided with a fresh threat.

entries.title: Read the memos Amazon execs sent to employees about job cuts
entries.description: Amazon's HR boss and retail chief sent memos to staff Wednesday saying the company had begun eliminating jobs.

entries.title: Fake cannabis billionaire Justin Costello pleads guilty in $35 million fraud, with recommended prison term of 10 years
entries.description: Justin Costello pretended to be a billionaire, a Special Forces veteran and Harvard MBA as he duped hundreds of people in a large fraud, prosecutors say.

entries.title: Amazon, Meta and Google buy more clean energy than any other companies
entries.description: While companies across the board have been steadily increasing their acquisition of wind and solar power, the tech sector has dominated.

entries.title: We welcome Cisco CEO's upbeat view on the economy, but remain cautious on future order growth
entries.description: The chief executive of Club holding Cisco Systems (CSCO) on Wednesday continued to strike a confident note on the state of the economy.

entries.title: Floods devastate Philippines as president declares 'state of calamity'
entries.description: The Philippines is ranked among the most vulnerable countries to climate-related disasters, but it is a minor contributor to global climate change.

entries.title: Ireland signals 'better mood' on UK-EU talks after bitter Brexit disputes
entries.description: Ireland's finance minister spoke of the new optimism and constructiveness surrounding talks between the U.K. and the EU following months of bitter post-Brexit trade disputes.

entries.title: The threat of a transatlantic trade war is dominating Davos
entries.description: The pressure is on the European institutions — but the question is how far are they willing to go?

entries.title: Microsoft, Amazon and other tech companies have laid off more than 60,000 employees in the last year
entries.description: The tech industry has seen a string of layoffs in the face of uncertain economic conditions.

entries.title: Markets fully price in quarter-point interest rate hike in February as inflation slows
entries.description: Pricing Wednesday morning pointed to a 94.3% probability of a 0.25 percentage point hike at the Federal Reserve's two-day meeting that concludes Feb. 1.

entries.title: Ukraine’s Zelenskyy tells Davos supplies of Western tanks must outpace another Russian offensive
entries.description: Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelenskyy on Wednesday said the supplies of Western tanks must outpace another Russian attack.

entries.title: Federal Reserve Chairman Jerome Powell tests positive for Covid
entries.description: Powell is experiencing "mild symptoms," according to the announcement.

entries.title: Iran has an obligation to give up its nuclear program, Saudi minister says
entries.description: The International Atomic Energy Agency has previously raised the alarm that "only countries making bombs" are enriching uranium at Iran's level.

entries.title: David Solomon admits Goldman took on too much, too quickly in consumer business
entries.description: "We obviously had a disappointing quarter, and we tried to own that, you know, up front," Solomon told CNBC's "Squawk Box" on Wednesday.

entries.title: Ripple CEO is optimistic the crypto firm will get ruling on XRP lawsuit soon, slams 'embarrassing' SEC
entries.description: Ripple CEO Brad Garlinghouse said he is optimistic a judge will issue a ruling on its legal dispute with the Securities and Exchange Commission this year.

entries.title: Oil giant Aramco says windfall taxes 'not helpful' and could stifle decarbonization
entries.description: The energy debate has been dominated by tensions between the need for energy security and a desire for cleaner energy sources to combat climate change.

entries.title: Microsoft is laying off 10,000 employees
entries.description: Microsoft said it's letting go of 10,000 employees and taking a $1.2 billion charge as the software maker braces for slower top-line growth.

entries.title: IEA chief expects Russia to lose the energy battle, sees major difficulties for Moscow's exports
entries.description: IEA Executive Director Fatih Birol's comments come shortly after an independent analysis showed that revenues from Russia's fossil fuel exports collapsed in December.

entries.title: Wholesale prices fell 0.5% in December, much more than expected
entries.description: The producer price index was expected to decrease 0.1% in December, according to Dow Jones estimates.

entries.title: Filmmaker Oliver Stone slams environmental movement over 'destructive' actions on nuclear
entries.description: The writer and director made his comments during an interview with CNBC's Tania Bryer at the World Economic Forum in Davos, Switzerland.

entries.title: John Kerry says thawing U.S.-China tensions could make a huge difference to climate fight
entries.description: The U.S. and China formally resumed stalled climate talks with China late last year following a meeting between President Joe Biden and President Xi Jinping.

entries.title: Bank of America CEO says capitalism needs cleaning up with new global ESG rules
entries.description: Brian Moynihan said the world needs a global standards line so business and society can say, "if you're below it we shouldn't do business with you."

entries.title: Aramco chief warns of possible oil supply shortages, as Chinese demand set to surge
entries.description: The latest IEA oil market report forecasts global oil demand will hit a record 101.7 million barrels per day this year — with nearly half of that coming from China.

entries.title: Credit Suisse CEO says outflows have reduced 'very significantly' as overhaul progresses
entries.description: Credit Suisse is seeing a sharp reduction in client outflows, as the embattled Swiss lender progresses with its major strategic overhaul, new CEO Ulrich Koerner told CNBC on Wednesday.

entries.title: Putin could be ready to announce a second mobilization drive
entries.description: Russian President Vladimir Putin could be ready to announce another mobilization round, as Moscow looks to bolster its armed forces in Ukraine, analysts believe.

entries.title: China's economy will be 'on fire' in the second half of 2023, StanChart chairman says
entries.description: China's economy will be "on fire" in the second half of 2023 as the economic performance of East and West diverges, according to Standard Chartered Chairman José Viñals.

entries.title: ‘Big Oil peddled the big lie’: UN chief slams energy giants for ignoring their own climate science
entries.description: U.N. Secretary-General Antonio Guterres on Wednesday condemned fossil fuel giants for ignoring their own climate science.

entries.title: Over 200 millionaires urge Davos elite to up taxes on the ultra-rich
entries.description: Over 200 millionaires called on the elite attendees of this week’s World Economic Forum in Davos to “tackle extreme wealth” and “tax the ultra-rich.”

entries.title: UniCredit CEO says Europe may defy the odds and avoid a recession
entries.description: Recent data points suggest the euro zone may defy the odds and avoid a recession, according to Andrea Orcel, CEO of Italian bank UniCredit.

entries.title: UK inflation rate dips for second straight month to hit 10.5%
entries.description: The core CPI, which excludes food, energy, alcohol and tobacco, was steady on the month at 6.3% in December, the ONS found.

entries.title: Top business leaders and policymakers discuss the future of jobs at the World Economic Forum
entries.description: Moderated by CNBC's Geoff Cutmore, top business leaders discuss at Davos, Switzerland, the impact the green transition, technological advances, demographics and reorganized value chains could have on labor markets.

entries.title: Naftogaz CEO says the Ukrainian state energy giant will be out of default soon
entries.description: Naftogaz was the first Ukrainian government-owned entity to default since Russia invaded the country in February.

entries.title: $1.4 trillion wipeout hits crypto industry at Davos — except for a lone flashy orange bitcoin car
entries.description: After the 2022 crypto crash, fewer crypto companies were features on the Davos Promenade as the industry keeps spending in check.

entries.title: China's economy looks set for a rebound in 2023, but a lot depends on one variable, KraneShares says
entries.description: "As external demand falls due to an impending recession in the West, China's economy must rely more heavily on the consumer," said KraneShares.

entries.title: Stopping the 'quiet quitting' trend could be all down to your boss
entries.description: Quiet quitting can become an issue over time, but it is up to managers to address it, business leaders said at the World Economic Forum in Davos.

entries.title: Japanese yen weakens as Bank of Japan makes no changes to yield curve range
entries.description: The Japanese currency weakened against the U.S. dollar after the Bank of Japan surprised markets by keeping its yield curve tolerance band unchanged.

entries.title: Recession fears won't stop 'the big quit' in 2023, says LinkedIn
entries.description: Professionals are displaying confidence, optimism and resilience post-pandemic despite recessionary fears, LinkedIn told CNBC Make It.

entries.title: Where are the safest places to travel in 2023? It depends on how you define 'safe'
entries.description: New reports show the "safest" travel destinations vary by whether crime, terrorism, quality of medical care or people's perceptions are analyzed.

entries.title: Twitter is auctioning off espresso machines and kegerators from its San Francisco headquarters
entries.description: Among the numerous kitchen supplies that Twitter is selling includes a rotisserie cooker, multiple refrigerators and pizza ovens.
